This paper deals with the Delaunay triangulation of moving points in the plane, which is a classic problem in computational geometry (cs.CG). The analysis is based on topological properties of the motion, which suggests that it may also be relevant to the study of dynamical systems (cs.DS) and control theory (cs.SY). The paper also discusses the maximum number of discrete changes in the triangulation, which is related to the concept of persistence in topological data analysis (cs.GR). Finally, the paper presents experimental results on random point sets, which may be of interest to researchers in machine learning and data mining (cs.MM).
